title: Hudson Yards
description: Hudson Yards, the area on the far west side of Manhattan between 30th and 43rd streets, is the site of the largest contemporary real estate development project in the United States, a venture spearheaded by the New York City Department of City Planning and Metropolitan Transportation Authority (MTA). The site, a rail yard, has been rezoned for commercial and residential development and will house what is essentially a neighborhood built from scratch. The project is an alternative to another, failed redevelopment idea that was based on New York City hosting the 2012 Summer Olympics and the construction of a sports stadium. The Related Companies and Oxford Property Group are the developers charged with building the core of the current site: millions of square feet of commercial and residential space, including 5,000 apartments, a hotel, a public school, and approximately 12 acres of public open space on the 26-acre site. The neighborhood is served by the 11th Avenue subway station of the 7 line, which opened in 2015. -TA

presented_by: Vornado Realty Trust, Josh Glick, Jared Solomon
title: 666 Fifth Avenue
description:
The 1.5 million-square-foot office and retail development at 666 Fifth Avenue has been the subject of a number of record-setting deals. Kushner Companies bought the property for $1.8 billion in 2007, at the time the most ever paid for a single office building in the U.S.
After the 2008 global financial crisis struck, in early 2010 Kushner's $1.215 billion loan was sent to special loan servicer LNR, in which Vornado Realty Trust would later take a stake. Kushner split the retail space into two condominiums, selling the smaller, 36,473-square-foot space to Inditex, parent company of fashion brand Zara, for $324 million or $8,300 per square foot on a blended basis, the highest price ever paid for commercial property larger than 10,000 square feet in New York City. Vornado bought a controlling 49.5 percent interest in the office condominium for $80 million in December 2011, and took the remaining 40,742-square-foot retail condo for $707 million in July 2012.
The 39-story 1957 building, designed by Carson & Lundin, stretches from 52nd Street to 53rd Street and includes landmarked lobby artwork: Isamu Noguchi's "Ceiling and Waterfall" installation.

title: Long Island City
description: Long Island City, or LIC, is a neighborhood in western Queens with waterfront on the East River. It is bounded by Hazen Street, 49th Street, New Calvary Cemetery, and Newtown Creek. The neighborhood contains the eastern terminus of the Queensboro Bridge, also known as the 59th Street Bridge, and the Queensbridge Houses, a massive government-subsidized housing complex controlled by the New York City Housing Authority. The formerly industrial waterfront area of LIC has become the site of redevelopment into luxury residential condominium and rental buildings. These include the Linc LIC and One Murray Park. Property Markets Group and the Hakim Organization are in the process of developing the 914-foot-tall residential building, dubbed, Queens Plaza Park, scheduled for completion after 2018. LIC is home to the tallest office building of the outer boroughs, One Court Square, also known as the Citigroup Building. -TA

title: Upper East Side
description: The Upper East Side is a neighborhood in Manhattan, bounded by 59th Street, 96th Street, the Hudson and East Rivers. Grand apartment houses, mostly cooperatives, along Fifth Avenue, Park Avenue, and cross streets in between contain some of the most expensive housing in the United States. A duplex penthouse at 1060 Fifth Avenue sold for $48.8 million in 2008. In 2006, the Harkness Mansion, a townhouse at 4 East 75th Street, traded for $53 million. Museums along Fifth Avenue include the Frick Collection, the Guggenheim Museum, and the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The Yorkville subsection of the neighborhood, north of 79th street and east of Third Avenue contains much cheaper housing. Its rental buildings attract recent college graduates. The official resident of the mayor, Gracie Mansion, is also located in Yorkville, in Carl Schurz Park at East End Avenue and 88th Street. Other subsections of the Upper East Side are Lenox Hill and Carnegie Hill. Thanks to its stock of former mansions and relative proximity to the United Nations, the neighborhood is home to many diplomatic missions, including the consulates of France at 934 Fifth Avenue and Italy at 690 Park Avenue. Wednesday Martin, a memoirist, documented the life of an Upper East Side mom in her book Primates of Park Avenue, published in 2015. -GB

title: 666 Third Avenue
description:
The Chrysler Building East at 666 Third Avenue is a 769,948-square-foot office tower in Midtown, Manhattan. It was built in 1952, developed by Walter P. Chrysler, and designed by Reinhard, Hofmeister & Walquist architects. Tishman Speyer bought the building in 1998, but Madison International Realty has a substantial stake at 48.9%.
The Chrysler Building East biggest lease is 73,668-square-feet by law firm Mintz Levin Cohn Ferris Glovsky and Popeo. Other major tenants include the European Union, The Government of The Netherlands and Wells Fargo Bank.
-WP

title: Williamsburg
description: Williamsburg is a neighborhood in northern Brooklyn, bounded by Greenpoint to the north, Bedford-Stuyvesant to the south, Bushwick to the east, and the East River to the west. A rezoning of the neighborhood in 2005 facilitated residential development, which has been most pronounced on the waterfront. As of 2015, factories that made sugar, shoe polish, mustard and musical instruments were in the process of being converted or have been converted into loft-style housing. Contemporary upscale condominiums include the Edge at 34 North 7th Street and Toll Brothers' Northside Piers at 164 Kent Avenue. The L train of the New York City subway system services Williamsburg; its Bedford Avenue station is the first stop outside downtown Manhattan. Service to Manhattan is due to shut down for 18 months starting early in 2019, however, to repair East River tunnel damage caused by Superstorm Sandy.

title: 7 Hanover Square
description:
7 Hanover Square, or The Guardian Life Building, is an 845,000-square-foot office building in the Financial District in Lower Manhattan. It was developd by Swig, Weiler & Arlow and built in 1983 in the postmodernist style. The building was designed by Emery Roth & Sons architects and is currently owned by Milstein Properties.
Building namesake The Guardian Life Insurance Company of America occupy more than half of the building with their 569,992-square-foot lease covering nearly 20 floors. Other major leases include law firm Fragomen, Del Rey, Bernsen & Loewry (117,091-square-feet), the International Business Times (46,176-square-feet) and New York Legal Assistance Group (34,511-square-feet).
In 2012, the basement of the building experienced severe flooding as a result of the effects of Hurricane Sandy.

title: 111 Eighth Avenue
description: 111 Eighth Avenue is an Art Deco building in the Chelsea neighborhood of Manhattan. The 2.9 million-square-foot building occupies a full city block bounded by Eighth and Ninth Avenues and 15th and 16th Streets. Architecture firm Lusby Simpson of Abbott, Merkt & Co. designed the building for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, which completed it in 1932. 111 Eighth Avenue initially operated as a freight and storage hub. When railroad operations dwindled in Manhattan at the turn of the century, it became the headquarters of the Port Authority until the government agency moved to the first World Trade Center complex in 1970. Taconic Investment Partners acquired it in 1998 as part of a portfolio of assets that also included 95 and 99 Wall Street and 100 William Street. At the time, warehouse tenants occupied much of the property and Midtown South was not considered a white-collar business district. The buildings printing and warehouse tenants moved out and Taconic repositioned it as office space geared to media and technology companies. In 2010, Google, one of the buildings tenants, acquired 111 Eighth Avenue for $1.77 billion from Taconic. The real estate investment firm continued to manage the property on Googles behalf, as of September 2015. -GB & TA

title: 553 West 30th Street
description: 553 West 30th Street is a 17,816 square foot building built in 2016 in the Hudson Yards neighborhood of Manhattan. The property has 285 total units. The building was completed in May of 2016.

title: 375 Hudson Street
description:
375 Hudson Street, also known as the Saatchi & Saatchi Building, is a commercial office, 18-story high-rise building in the Soho neighborhood of Manhattan. The building contains 1,011,937-square-feet. It was completed in 1989 and its design was a collaborative effort between Emery Roth & Sons, Lee Harris Pomeroy Associates, and Skidmore, Owings and Merrill. In 2010, the building achieved LEED Gold certification for sustainability and energy efficiency.
The building is the headquarters of namesake advertising firm Saatchi & Saatchi, Penguin Group, and Turner Construction Company. Saatchi & Saatchi occupies the most space in the building, 692,325-square-feet , with Penguin Group coming in next at 223,485-square-feet. Tishman Speyer owns the building, which it controls through a ground lease with Trinity Wall Street, which owns the fee.
-WP

title: Manhattan Plaza
description:
Manhattan Plaza is a 46-story, 1,688-unit, federally-subsidized housing tower located at 400 West 43rd Street, just west of Times Square. It occupies an entire block, bounded by 43rd Street, Ninth Avenue, 42nd Street, and Tenth Avenue. The developers who erected the building, designed by architect David Todd, in 1977 intended it to be luxury apartments, but went bankrupt. Seventy percent of the buildings units are occupied by performing artists with the balance occupied by community elderly and community low-income residents.
In 2003, Related Companies, a developer and landlord, acquired the complex from Manhattan Plaza Associates LP, a partnership headed by Richard Ravitch and Irving Fischer. Related Chief Executive Stephen M. Ross said in 2004 that his company planned to extend the buildings Section 8 contract, which runs to 2017. Building amenities include a playground, five tennis courts, and gym, a swimming pool, and a 1,000-car garage. The Laurie Beechman Theatre, formerly the West Bank Cafe Downstairs Theater Bar, is a dinner theater located in the basement of the building. Manhattan Plaza also has 50,000 square feet of retail space at its base.
-MK

title: 40 West 57th Street
description:
40 West 57th Street is a 712,000-square-foot, 428-foot tall office skyscraper in Midtown, Manhattan. The building was built in 1972 and was designed by architect Jack Brown. It was developed by Samuel J. LeFrak and is owned by the LeFrak Organization, who also has its main offices there.
The building has a number of large leases. Clothing retailer Nautica has a 120,000-square-foot office that covers four floors. Elliott Management leases 100,042-square-feet in the building. In the mid-2000s rents at 40 West 57th Street doubled in just five years.

title: Bushwick
description: Bushwick is a neighborhood in northern Brooklyn, bounded by Flushing Avenue, Broadway, the borough of Queens and the Cemetery of the Evergreens. Some real estate market participants call it East Williamsburg and sometimes include the industrial area north of Flushing Avenue in the neighborhood, calling it Industrial Bushwick. Knickerbocker Avenue is Bushwick's main shopping street. The neighborhood owes its rising property prices to the proximity of Williamsburg to the west and the fact that the popular L subway line runs through it and into downtown Manhattan (though service to Manhattan will stop for 18 months starting in early 2019 to repair tunnel damage from Superstorm Sandy). Housing stock consists mostly of two- to three-family row houses and midsize apartment buildings. Hundreds of units in the neighborhood are government-subsidized. As in Williamsburg in the 1990s, Bushwick's warehouses have been repurposed as artists' studios or as sites for large parties. Manhattan and Williamsburg transplants, in search of cheaper housing and more space, have been pushing out Bushwick's immigrant and Latino population. As of 2015, Dallas-based developer Lincoln Property Company was converting a 100,000-square-foot factory at 455 Jefferson Street into an office building with retail space. Bushwick Realty Holdings LLC, controlled by Brooklyn landlord Moshe Braver, plans to build a 180-unit residential apartment building at 338 Evergreen Avenue. Other residential developments include 330 Bleecker Street, 13 Melrose Street, Colony 1209 at 1209 DeKalb Avenue, 51 Troutman Street and 95 Evergreen.

title: Chelsea
description: Chelsea is a neighborhood on the west side of Manhattan, bounded by 14th Street, 30th Street, the Avenue of the Americas (Sixth Avenue), and the Hudson River and West Street. The neighborhood was known for its gay and lesbian residents and art galleries, but this characteristic has given way to high-end condominiums populated by transplanted urban professionals as rents and land prices have risen across New York City. JDS Development converted The Walker Tower, an old Verizon building at 210 West 18th Street into upscale condominiums. In 2010, internet search giant Google acquired a warehouse-to-tech office conversion at 111 Eighth Avenue that was at one time owned by The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey. The rent-stabilized residents of The Chelsea Hotel on 23rd Street have so far resisted the efforts of a series of developers hoping to conduct a condo-conversion at the cultural landmark. -TA

title: 3 Columbus Circle
description:
3 Columbus Circle is a 310-foot office skyscraper in Midtown, Manhattan. The original building, known as the Colonnade Building, had only three stories and was constructed in 1923. Four years later, a tower designed by Shreve & Lamb architects was built on top of it. The building is part of Columbus Circle, a traffic circle featuring a Christopher Columbus monument at the southwest corner of Central Park.
In 2011, New York realty company SL Green acquired 48.9% ownership in the building from developer Joseph Moinian who was was facing foreclosure. The sale price was reported to be $500 million. Moinian had originally bought the building in 2004 for $250 million.
Current tenants at the building include Young & Rubicam, who occupy nearly 44% of the building with their 340,000-square-foot headquarters, nearly 215,000 square feet of which Young & Rubicam bought as a commercial condo. Bank of America, Chase Bank, and Gilder Gagnon Howe & Co. also hold leases at the building.
-WP

title: 622 Third Avenue
description:
622 Third Avenue is a 41-story commercial and office building, one of several owned by Cohen Brothers in Manhattans Grand Central District. The building, completed in 1974, has a 986,441 square foot gross floor area.
The building, a;so known as Grand Central Plaza, was renovated in the early 2010s to the tune of about $5 million 2000 to make it LEED-certified. During the renovation, well-known architects Moed de Armas & Shannon updated the lobby with skylights and elegant light fixtures. The buildings outdoor plaza was also updated from its previous mid-70s design.
622 Third Avenue is just steps from Grand Central Station, making it the ideal location for commuters as well as a hub for city subways.
In 2012, Charles Cohen of Cohen Brothers told the New York Observer that he was seeing rents in the $50s to $60s per square foot for about 200,000 of the buildings roughly 900,000 square feet as leases were set to expire. Three Park Avenue will also get a lobby facelift, whereas a more significant upgrade is taking place at 475 Park Avenue South, which is getting a faÂade replacement and a lobby renovation.
-GM

title: Staten Island
description: Staten Island, with its population of 473,279, is the least populous and most suburban of New York CityÍs five boroughs. The 1964 opening of the Verrazano Bridge, which connected the borough to Brooklyn, drove development of the previously rural area and doubled its population. Its northern edge is dotted with denser, more urban neighborhoods like St. George, Tompkinsville, Clifton, and Stapleton, which are close the terminal for the ferry to Lower Manhattan. The southern end of the island is more leafy. One could mistake its streets, lined with large single-family homes, with yards and pools, for a bedroom community in upstate New York. Staten Island is not connected to the rest of New York City Subway system, except by the ferry, unlike the other four boroughs. The rapid rise of real estate prices has not bypassed Staten Island, which has seen its share of development as a result. In 2011, the city sold seven waterfront acres in the Stapleton neighborhood for $11 million to Ironstate Development. A 900-unit rental complex, plus retail and parking, is scheduled for completion by the end of 2015. The city is also leading the redevelopment of the waterfront around the ferry terminal and the Richmond County Ballpark. In order to attract tourists to the borough, developers are planning to build the biggest Ferris wheel in the world in St. George. -TA

title: Harlem
description: Harlem is a neighborhood in upper Manhattan, bounded by Central Park, Fifth Avenue, 155th Street, and the Hudson River, and sometimes described using the shorthand uptown. Subsections of the neighborhood include Morningside Heights, Manhattanville, Hamilton Heights, Central Harlem, and East Harlem. In the last 100 years, Harlem has functioned as a major center of African-American culture. However, land prices and rents in Harlem have risen in tandem with the rest of New York City since the financial crisis, contributing to the neighborhood ñturning overî, as longtime residents who cannot afford it move away and wealthier New Yorkers move in. Columbia University is building a 17-acre satellite campus in the post-industrial Manhattanville subsection of Harlem, scheduled for completion in 2016. New developments in Harlem include The Adeline, One Morningside Park on 110th Street, and Uptown 58 on 129th Street. Specialty and organic food purveyor Whole Foods is scheduled to open a grocery store on 125th Street and Lenox Avenue in 2016. -TA

title: Industry City
description:
882 Third Avenue in Brooklyn's Sunset Park neighborhood is a waterfront industrial complex completed in 1906 and also known as Industry City. The complex hosts some of the city's largest floor plates, at roughly 160,000 square feet; it is a mixed industrial and manufacturing parcel divided into 42 separate units.
The renovated site is just south of the southern tip of Manhattan, perched between the Gowanus Expressway and New York Harbor.
In August 2013,  Jamestown Properties, Belvedere Capital and Angelo, Gordon & Co. bought a stake in the property. Billionaire Rubin Schron's Cammeby's International, and FBE Limited are also partners. The owners unveiled plans in early 2015 to invest close to $1 billion over 12 years to create a modern manufacturing and technology hub; plans call for upgrading the 6 million-square-foot complex's infrastructure, development of a university-based research facility, an employment office and almost 1 million square feet of retail space.
Tenants include everything from artists to technology firms, and the 3-D printer company MakerBot Industries and flavor maker Virginia Dare Extract Co. lease space there.
The Brooklyn Nets National Basketball Association team, which plays at downtown Brooklyn's Barclays Center, is constructing a practice court on a rooftop at the complex.
The Jamestown group is seeking the city's help to upgrade the area surrounding Industry City.

presented_by: Vornado Realty Trust, Josh Glick, Edward Riguardi, Edward Hogan, Meredith Fales
title: 1290 Avenue of the Americas
description:
The 2.1-million-square-foot building at 1290 Sixth Avenue was built in 1963 and renovated in 2012-2013. The property stretches from 51st Street to 52nd Street on the eastern side of the avenue and includes 43 office floors and two concourse levels. Vornado Realty Trust, which has a 70 percent interest in the property, signed a 10-year, $950 million refinance at 3.3 percent in November 2012.
Asking rents in the building are in the $70s per square foot. In May 2013, Morgan Stanley signed an 11-year sublease of 148,421 square feet from AXA Equitable; investment firm Neuberger Berman is set to take up about 400,000 square feet at the end of 2016. Other tenants include Hachette Book Group, which signed a deal in December 2013 to replace Microsoft in 137,000 square feet, and State Street Bank, with 106,000 square feet.

owner: Blackstone Group, Wharton Properties, SL Green
title: 717 Fifth Avenue
description:
717 Fifth Avenue, also knowns as the Corning Glass Works Building and the Merrill Lynch Financial Center, is a 25-story, 357-foot office skyscraper in Midtown, Manhattan. It was designed by Harrison & Abramovitz architects in the international style. The building was completed in 1958. The lobby features a mural painted by Bauhaus artist Josef Albers. The building contains 468,000 square feet.
The tower is majority owned by the Blackstone Group, with minority stakes held by Jeff Sutton and SL Green, who own ground floor retail condominiums whose tenants include Armani and Dolce & Gabana. At the time of joint venture acquisition in 2006, SL Green had 32.75% ownership. However, SL Green now maintains a 10.92% stake at 717 Fifth Avenue, the majority of their stake having been bought out by Sutton in 2012.
Office tenants at the address include Andrew Farkas Island Capital Group, Merrill Lynch/Bank of America, and JC Flowers.
-WP

owner: RXR Realty, Edward J. Minskoff Equities, Marsh & McLennan
title: 1166 Avenue of the Americas
description:
The 1.6 million-square-foot, 44-floor, Class A office tower at 1166 Avenue of the Americas is one of the more prestigious buildings in Midtown, and a lot of that has to do with its tenant roster, which includes Bank of America, MetLife, American Express, Interpublic Group, JP Morgan Chase, Conde Nast, Morgan Stanley, Time Inc. and UBS
The tower has quite the footprint, too, occupying the entire block front of Sixth Avenue from 45th to 46th streets (individual floors can run to more than 40,000 square feet). Skidmore Owings & Merrill designed it, and the predecessor to Tishman Speyer developed it; it was finished in 1974. The tower also goes by 1166 Sixth Avenue.
The ownership structure for 1166 Avenue of the Americas is a bit complicated. It is divided into three office condos, each hundreds of thousands of square feet. Owners with major stakes in the tower include RXR Realty, a privately held real estate investment firm; Edward J. Minskoff Equities; and Marsh & McLennan, a financial advisory firm. -TA

title: 1166 Avenue of the Americas
description:
Located in Lenox Hill, the Trump Park Avenue at 502 Park Avenue is one of Donald Trumps most coveted properties, but it has little of his trademark grandeur. Located in the hoighty-toighty Lenox Hill neighborhood of New York City, and unfortunately built in in 1929 on the cusp of the Great Depression, the building has changed hands (and names) several times. For years it had been home to a number of hotels: first the Viceroy, then the Cromwell Arms, and finally Hotel Delmonico, where it was home to several celebrities, including Ed Sullivan, and the alleged location of where Bob Dylan introduced marijuana to the Beatles.
In 2001 Trump bought the building for $115 million and within a couple years converted it from a hotel into a 120-unit luxury residential condominium, though with the intention of keeping some hotel-esque features like maid and laundry service. The building still has touches of pre-war, including hand-laid brick, but Trump has pumped nearly $100 million into renovating it.
Today the property continues to hue to its star-hugging past. A number of high-profile renters have lived there, including the owner of the New York Giants, infamous baseball player Alex Rodriguez, and Rupert Murdoch.
-NR
